<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 9:23<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If64e45e16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I4b277990933c11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>9.</label.designator><headtext>Effect of Transfer: Proceedings in the Transferee Court</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94f9de10e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>9:23.</label.designator><headtext>Disposition in the transferee court—Transfer of case to transferee court for trial</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Historically, one important means of resolving transferred cases in the transferee court was transfer of the cases to that court for trial. <eos/><bos/>Transfer in this manner is not ordered by the Panel, but by the transferee court itself. <eos/><bos/>The 1998 decision of the Supreme Court in <cite.query w-src-number="0304914128" w-serial-number="1998061318" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RS" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I7381c6a26b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">Lexecon Inc. v. Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes &amp; Lerach</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="If64e45e26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] halted this practice of self-transfer, because of the express language of <cite.query w-src-number="0304914128" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I738289f06b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">28 U.S.C.A. § 1407</cite.query> limiting transfer to pretrial proceedings and requiring remand when those proceedings are complete.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If64e6cf16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>] The legislative history of the statute similarly reflects an intention to limit transfer to pretrial proceedings.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If64e6cf36b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">3</footnote.reference>] Even before Lexecon, however, transferee courts would sometimes deny motions to transfer cases to themselves for trial.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If64e6cf56b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The impact of the prohibition on self-transfer also prevents the court from transferring pursuant to statute[<footnote.reference refid="If64f09306b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">5</footnote.reference>] a case where personal jurisdiction is lacking to a district where the case could have been commenced, where the effect of transfer there would have the effect of re-transfer to the MDL transferee district.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If64f09316b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If64e45e16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If64e45e26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0304914128" w-serial-number="1998061318" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I73823bd26b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">Lexecon Inc. v. Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes &amp; Lerach, 523 U.S. 26, 118 S. Ct. 956, 140 L. Ed. 2d 62 (1998)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>Lexecon is discussed in greater detail in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs3:14" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If64e6cf06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 3:14</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If64e6cf16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0304914128" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I7382b1006b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">28 U.S.C.A. § 1407(a)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The limited scope of transfer is discussed in greater detail in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs3:2" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If64e6cf26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 3:2</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If64e6cf36b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>For discussion of the legislative history of <cite.query w-src-number="0304914128" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I7382ff206b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">28 U.S.C.A. § 1407(a)</cite.query>, see <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs2:3" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If64e6cf46b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 2:3</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If64e6cf56b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See, e.g.,</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304914128" w-serial-number="1973104591" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="276" ID="I738374516b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">In re Air Crash Disaster at Greater Cincinnati Airport, 354 F. Supp. 275, 276 &amp; n.1 (J.P.M.L. 1973)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If64f09306b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304914128" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1631" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I7383c2706b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">28 U.S.C.A. § 1631</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If64f09316b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0304914128" w-serial-number="2039164416" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0007903" w-pinpoint-page="1123" ID="I738437a16b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">In re Chiquita Brands International, Inc. Alien Tort Statute and Shareholder Derivative Litigation, 190 F. Supp. 3d 1100, 1123 (S.D. Fla. 2016)</cite.query>, citing <cite.query w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MCLANNs20.132" w-pub-number="0148162" ID="I738437a26b3e11e9976996f337230435">David F. Herr, Annotated Manual for Complex Litigation (Fourth) § 20.132 (2014 ed.)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><